JzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV=
00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL2FuLWludGVy=
dmlldy13aXRoLWFuZHVyaWwtZm91bmRlci1hbmQtY2VvLWJyaWFuLXNjaGltcGYtYWJvdXQtc29=
mdHdhcmUtYW5kLXRoZS1taWxpdGFyeS8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTczNjk0NzI5MSwiaWF0IjoxNzM0Mz=
U1MjkxLCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6I=
mZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVt=
ZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.GVFT=
mtrlens7v65vN65j8Qa90fmRgV3v2ODIk_U4uwFHCFFCqL9CYzPwUEPK2SzruYciMT9l5lnF7yC=
Hf2iRWJkd_yCV6Fo1jdB2w44AfI89o-f_nwLCOwWt1iP12kn5NVdMvVXOq12_Gc-qaywFLo3Uij=
jqyx2369TKY95rGKabS7C__Q7_yP5_il1qaM5XQkcr1p834HIfbq4t1iaH2QRFh7hx0iExaYoGP=
SbCLlJ4DpB88ooSrLD5r1lkMg28AkWPqMbF60Gp4w0dFSqP63ebAr8PQUMZ_pxrox2VugP-1uJZ=
Gy9tEg4Gb21yPZaUSaVSQI1UThBJGk8yNkccGg ) and I introduced Lattice this way =
(I=E2=80=99m going to selectively copy-and-paste from the interview extensi=
vely, but I recommend the whole thing):

*When you think about a defense contractor, you think about hardware, weapo=
ns of war. We sort of joked about that at the very beginning, and the promp=
t to have you on Stratechery now was the announcement of this new drone fig=
hter Fury ( https://www.anduril.com/fury/ ) , which we=E2=80=99ll get to in=
 a little bit. But what you=E2=80=99re saying, and I think rings true to me=
, is that hardware is probably the wrong frame of reference for thinking ab=
out Anduril and why you are fundamentally different than other defense cont=
ractors.*

*BS:* Yeah, I think that=E2=80=99s right. I mean, look, at the end of the d=
ay, the DOD, the Department of Defense, they know how to buy hardware. They=
 can count the number of planes, they know why it costs money, they can cou=
nt the number of missiles. There=E2=80=99s a very clear understanding of wh=
at a price for that should be, what you=E2=80=99re paying for and what you=
=E2=80=99re getting, it=E2=80=99s very obvious. The government does not bel=
ieve it will run a factory to produce these things on the whole. There=E2=
=80=99s some things they produce, which is very random, but the software si=
de is not that today.

So the software side, it is constantly a discussion and debate around how m=
uch of the government own the IP, what should the structures be, how do you=
 get the incentives you want out of industry? It=E2=80=99s a really tricky =
problem. Where you look at it from the government=E2=80=99s perspective, th=
ey=E2=80=99re sort of like, =E2=80=9CWell, it doesn=E2=80=99t cost you to m=
ake marginal copies of this, so why am I paying you?=E2=80=9D And you look =
at it from the software companies perspective-

*Software is a pure R&D cost. It=E2=80=99s not a marginal cost, which doesn=
=E2=80=99t match up with the way government is paid for stuff traditionally=
.*

*BS:* Exactly. So you just have this massive mismatch, and that is a real c=
hallenge. So by doing the hardware side, we=E2=80=99re in a lot of ways abl=
e to wrap it in metal. The software is often the, =E2=80=9CWhy us?=E2=80=9D=
. It=E2=80=99s like we=E2=80=99re able to solve problems in an interesting =
and novel way because we can make them smarter, but it=E2=80=99s very hard =
to price that, understand that, know how that fits, but the hardware side e=
nables us to solve this.

The second piece of this is the hardware of what has been built to date is =
not designed around how do I have the right software APIs, control, be able=
 to deploy modern machine learning models into it, it=E2=80=99s just not ho=
w it works. It=E2=80=99s very hard-coded, it=E2=80=99s very baked, it=E2=80=
=99s very designed for manual control of these things, and so when you want=
 to apply all these advanced software techniques, it falls apart. So design=
ing hardware that=E2=80=99s open and API-driven from the beginning, that ha=
s enabled us to be extremely effective of how we tie these together as an i=
nteresting family of systems.

*So let me see if I have what you just articulated right from a big picture=
 perspective, I want to tie it all together. So you are a Silicon Valley st=
artup, and you are able then to get investors that understand the idea of i=
nvesting huge upfront amounts in R&D to build a software stack knowing that=
 you can monetize in the long run, so that lets you build this differentiat=
ed operating system, basically Lattice, that then in the long run will let =
you produce very highly capable weapons that are much more capable relative=
 to their marginal cost, which is highly differentiated. You could sell it =
to the military, =E2=80=9CLook, you can get this weapon for relatively chea=
p, that=E2=80=99s incredibly capable because we have this ability.=E2=80=9D=
 It=E2=80=99s because you did the R&D because you=E2=80=99re a software com=
pany, you have this massive go-to-market advantage in the long run for any =
weapons platform you want to build. Is that the good one-minute summary the=
re?*

*BS:* That=E2=80=99s basically spot on and that=E2=80=99s exactly how we th=
ink about the business.

If you grok this excerpt, you get why this announcement is a big deal. Andu=
ril isn=E2=80=99t in the hardware business, they=E2=80=99re in the software=
 business. Or, more specifically, Anduril isn=E2=80=99t a drone company, th=
ey=E2=80=99re an operating system company =E2=80=94 a true tech platform.

That =E2=80=9Cplatform=E2=80=9D word is funny; =E2=80=9Cplatform=E2=80=9D i=
s a word that the Department of Defense is familiar with, but with a very d=
ifferent meaning: in military terminology the F-35 is a platform, a submari=
ne is a platform, a tank is a platform, etc. These are self-contained produ=
cts that deliver weapons, operate sensors, transport humans, etc. They of c=
ourse have software =E2=80=94 a massive cost and major driver of delays =E2=
=80=94 but that software is custom-built for the hardware that it runs on. =
Note the word that I used above; in tech we call these =E2=80=9Cproducts=E2=
=80=9D.

A platform in tech, on the other hand, is the foundation for products, and =
is usually an operating system of some type. Windows is the preeminent exam=
ple: Windows provided defined APIs for hardware makers on one hand, creatin=
g a market for computers, peripherals, etc., and a set of software APIs on =
the other that let developers build applications that ran on Windows.

Platforms are extraordinarily valuable, both to the world and to the compan=
y that builds them. Again, look at Microsoft: an untold number of companies=
 owe their existence to the fact that the Windows platform existed, and the=
 productivity gains to the world from having a common platform for applicat=
ions were enormous. Microsoft, meanwhile, became the most valuable company =
in the world, and its founder the world=E2=80=99s richest man.

It=E2=80=99s hard to imagine a world without Windows =E2=80=94=C2=A0or iOS =
or Android or Linux or the Internet itself (not all platforms are technical=
ly operating systems, to be clear) =E2=80=94 because the benefits of platfo=
rms are so enormous, but give it a try: we might, for example, still use a =
word processor for typing, calculators for calculating, stereos for playing=
 music. Those are easy examples, because they existed before platforms, but=
 then you realize how much more we do on computers or smartphones that simp=
ly doesn=E2=80=99t make sense in world of dedicated hardware; moreover, act=
ually trying to operate across individual products would be unfeasible give=
n the impossibility of sharing and coordinating information.

That non-platform world, however, is military reality with its products-cal=
led-platforms; the DoD has ships and planes and submarines and tanks and ar=
tillery and radar and sonar, but the coordination layer is all humans, with=
 all of the lack of scalability and potential for error that entails. Moreo=
ver, there are a host of other potential weapons systems =E2=80=94 like the=
 myriad of apps on your smartphone =E2=80=94 that simply don=E2=80=99t exis=
t because they are impractical to build. Worse, this is a problem that is o=
nly becoming more acute, particularly with the explosion of data and the im=
portance of communication, which is exactly what Lattice is focused on.

Back to the interview:

*So I want to dive a little bit more into Lattice. You mentioned the three =
different platform or three areas that =E2=80=94 we=E2=80=99re using platfo=
rm too much, I have to avoid it =E2=80=94 the three different areas that yo=
u=E2=80=99re building products in, and that Lattice started in the sensor a=
rea. Was Lattice extended to all three, or do you have distinct operating s=
ystem platforms between those three?*

*BS:* We try to take it as one kind of holistic platform, and we really thi=
nk about it as more of a la carte umbrella where everything works together,=
 very similar to AWS, it=E2=80=99s like everything is going to work. You=E2=
=80=99re going to have the same security and networking across everything, =
and the same sort of model, but certain times you need different components=
.

At the crux of it, we think of it as networking layer at the base, so how d=
o I move data around between all these different assets, all these differen=
t systems? In light of the challenges that DOD has, which is everything is =
over a radio link, everything is getting jammed, interrupted, and the netwo=
rk is constantly changing. There=E2=80=99s no high-speed pipes that you can=
 really rely on.

Then we think of it as three different pieces of what you=E2=80=99re really=
 trying to do. One is sense-making =E2=80=94 how do I take all the sensors =
that are available in my environment and understand what is going on? In a =
self-driving car sense, this is like, =E2=80=9CWhere are lane lines? Am I s=
taying in the road?=E2=80=9D. In the defense world, this is typically, =E2=
=80=9CWhere is the adversary aircraft? Are those friendly aircraft or adver=
sary aircraft? What is their intent? What are they trying to do?=E2=80=9D A=
nd you=E2=80=99re pulling this from lots of different systems. So, that sen=
se-making piece is absolutely huge. So, we do that both on a single platfor=
m and we do this across platforms.

*And this really ties into the networking layer where if you get cut off fr=
om the network, can you still accomplish that in isolation? Does this scale=
 up from an individual weapon to a pod of weapons to the overall platform a=
nd it has to go up and down seamlessly?*

*BS:* That=E2=80=99s right. Yeah, it=E2=80=99ll go all the way from if I ge=
t fully cut off, I still complete my mission and do what I need to do local=
ly, to I talk to the team I have, to I start pulling in information and sha=
ring information with different granularities across the whole theater of o=
perations as I need to, and as I have availability. So, you can kind of thi=
nk about it operating at lots of different levels with lots of different in=
formation sharing at every stage.

But that sense-making is really key. In a lot of ways, that is what DOD doe=
s. They want to find out, =E2=80=9CWhere=E2=80=99s the adversary and how do=
 I engage them most effectively?=E2=80=9D either because I=E2=80=99m maneuv=
ering and I don=E2=80=99t want to get found, or I want to stop them or defe=
at them or knock out some capability. So, that targeting is a huge part of =
this and we think about that as one of the pillars of this. We do this acro=
ss computer vision, radar systems, radio signals, you name it, we=E2=80=99r=
e kind of working across a very wide array of sensors on that.

Then there=E2=80=99s the decision support side. So, =E2=80=9CHow do I have =
a user interface that actually enables people to make informed decisions wi=
th the right information at the right level?=E2=80=9D This is a really hard=
 challenge, which is when I=E2=80=99m talking about tasking and operating t=
hese systems, coming up with even the vocabulary of, =E2=80=9CHow I tell it=
 what to do and how do I interface with that and keep track of a whole batt=
le-space while an adversary=E2=80=99s trying to confuse you?=E2=80=9D, that=
=E2=80=99s very hard. We spend a lot of time on that user interface and, =
=E2=80=9CHow does this actually work?=E2=80=9D.

The third part is that, =E2=80=9CHow do I actually task these effects or ma=
ke these things happen in the real world?=E2=80=9D. This is where we add a =
lot of the autonomy functionality into what we do. This could be as simple =
as, =E2=80=9CTell a camera to go look somewhere=E2=80=9D. In the higher-end=
 cases, this is, =E2=80=9CHey, I have a team of aircraft and they=E2=80=99r=
e going to go look for radar systems and they=E2=80=99re going to fan out, =
get the right geometry to figure out exactly where they are, then as they i=
dentify them, get imagery of it and then you can decide, =E2=80=98Okay, now=
 I want to strike this one. Okay, what weapons do I have available?=E2=80=
=99 Go out and do it.=E2=80=9D

This is a platform, and it=E2=80=99s clearly necessary, but again, the DoD =
buys hardware, not software. That meant that Anduril had to sell weapons po=
wered by Lattice, not Lattice itself, which further meant integrating into =
hardware makers; I asked Schimpf about this:

*One thing that=E2=80=99s interesting is as part as the Fury announcement, =
you announced that you were acquiring Blue Force Technologies ( https://www=
.anduril.com/article/anduril-acquires-blue-force-technologies/ ) , which wo=
rked on Fury, and that was just like a week after you=E2=80=99d announced y=
ou were acquiring Adranos ( https://www.anduril.com/article/anduril-industr=
ies-acquires-solid-rocket-motor-manufacturer-adranos/ ) , which makes solid=
 rocket motors. You=E2=80=99ve acquired Area-I ( https://blog.anduril.com/a=
nduril-industries-acquires-area-i-adds-altius-capabilities-to-hardware-port=
folio-36633ebcc73b ) , Copious Imaging ( https://www.anduril.com/article/an=
duril-industries-acquires-copius-imaging/ ) , Dive Technologies ( https://w=
ww.anduril.com/article/anduril-industries-acquires-dive-technologies/ ).*

*I=E2=80=99m curious about this approach because I could see two explanatio=
ns here and maybe it=E2=80=99s both. One is Lattice is an operating system =
and there are network effects and there=E2=80=99s a bit where bringing that=
 into your network has compounding effects and for any startup going forwar=
d, this is the obvious exit path. Number two is Anduril has spent six years=
 figuring out the DOD and the sales process and how to get into it and that=
=E2=80=99s such a difficult task that it=E2=80=99s just easier to go via yo=
u if you=E2=80=99re someone new. Is it both those, is it a little bit A, li=
ttle bit of B?*

*BS:* Yeah, I think it=E2=80=99s both those. I think absolutely on the Latt=
ice network effects piece, I think it=E2=80=99s true. I think as we add mor=
e platforms, more sensors, more capabilities into this, everything gets mor=
e valuable, I think that=E2=80=99s spot on.

*Can a startup build for Lattice without being a part of Anduril or do they=
 have to be a part of Anduril?*

*BS:* We=E2=80=99ve definitely had third parties integrate. We=E2=80=99re l=
ooking at doing more of a partner program on this, its just such a weird sp=
ace in the DOD where the value story is pretty straightforward and if you=
=E2=80=99re an Apple or any of these things around, =E2=80=9CHow do you cap=
ture value on this, how do you create value?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99=
s such a simple win-win scenario, but in the DOD case, it=E2=80=99s quite h=
ard. It=E2=80=99s not obvious how you do this in a win-win scenario and so =
we=E2=80=99ve been playing with some different models on it.

*You can=E2=80=99t put up a developer site and let anyone download the SDK =
or whatever it is.*

*BS:* Exactly, right. But say we even did that, you=E2=80=99re like, =E2=80=
=9COkay, did I enable you to get access to a new market?=E2=80=9D, kind of,=
 but not really. You still had to go find these contracts and go through th=
is brutal sales cycle and then say I do this, =E2=80=9CCan I capture any so=
rt of revenue share or value from your integration with it?=E2=80=9D It=E2=
=80=99s like, =E2=80=9CNo, that=E2=80=99s not really how the contracting wo=
rks=E2=80=9D. So, it=E2=80=99s like figuring out this win-win story is quit=
e challenging, even if it=E2=80=99s exactly what the DOD wants, they ask fo=
r it all the time. Just figuring out how to get it there is not obvious fro=
m just the basic economic incentives.

*It feels like this is the workaround, right? Ideally the DOD would actuall=
y fix their process and understand that in a software world, you have to al=
low for R&D ahead of the purchase, but there=E2=80=99s a bit where Anduril=
=E2=80=99s becoming the API for the Pentagon, where if you want to actually=
 build something new, the way to get in is going to have to be via Anduril =
because the DOD is locked into this five defense contractor view of the wor=
ld that they themselves pushed and inspired the Last Dinner ( https://www.w=
bur.org/onpoint/2023/03/01/the-last-supper-how-a-1993-pentagon-dinner-resha=
ped-the-defense-industry ) a bit. It=E2=80=99s almost like you have a netwo=
rk effect on multiple levels, not just a software network effect, but like =
a channel network effect in some respects.*

*BS:* That=E2=80=99s right. And the channel side, I think, is to your secon=
d point actually huge. The ability to =E2=80=94 because when you sell these=
 DOD programs, it=E2=80=99s not just, =E2=80=9CDo you have the right tool?=
=E2=80=9D, it=E2=80=99s do you have the security infrastructure and the pro=
gram management support and the ability to do all the Hill and lobbying pie=
ces and work with the Pentagon? Do they believe you can scale? Do you have =
a production system that can scale your hardware? All of these are very, ve=
ry hard and these are areas where I think when we=E2=80=99ve done these acq=
uisitions, we=E2=80=99ve been able to accelerate these companies on all of =
those fronts. How do we actually make these even more successful and enable=
 them to scale much bigger?

This is where this week=E2=80=99s big update comes in. First, Anduril has i=
n fact put up a developer site ( https://www.anduril.com/lattice-partner-pr=
ogram/ ) and released an SDK. Secondly, there is encouraging news that the =
Pentagon is starting to understand what true platforms are all about. Two w=
eeks ago the Pentagon announced a new $100 million contract with Anduril ( =
https://www.defense.gov/News/Contracts/Contract/Article/3983769/ ) for soft=
ware , specifically Lattice; from Breaking Defense ( https://breakingdefens=
e.com/2024/12/decentralizing-battle-data-cdao-anduril-open-tactical-mesh-to=
-third-party-developers/ ) :

As the US military embraces artificial intelligence and big data, the Penta=
gon is trying to wean itself from reliance on centralized mega-systems and =
instead empower frontline leaders at the =E2=80=9Ctactical edge.=E2=80=9D T=
hat=E2=80=99s why, last week, the Pentagon=E2=80=99s Chief Digital & AI Off=
ice (CDAO) awarded startup defense firm Anduril a $100 million, three-year =
contract to expand its Lattice Mesh. Lattice is a system that lets frontlin=
e forces rapidly access data from over a hundred different types of sensors=
 =E2=80=94 for example, to track incoming hostile drones =E2=80=94 over exi=
sting tactical networks, without having to first relay that data through ce=
ntral processing hubs.

Then, this week, Anduril released a Lattice Software Development Kit (SDK) =
that will allow other companies to build their own applications to run on L=
attice Mesh, without having to get permission from Anduril. The company ann=
ounced an initial list of 10 partners, ranging from startups like Apex (spa=
ce systems) and Saronic (unmanned boats) to giants like Oracle and Textron.=
 But in the future, an Anduril executive told Breaking Defense, any company=
 can access the kit and write software for Lattice=E2=80=A6

It=E2=80=99s a decentralized business model for a decentralized military sy=
stem. It=E2=80=99s also a departure from traditional practice for both the =
defense industry and the Defense Department, which historically favor centr=
alized mega-projects where a single lead contractor can achieve =E2=80=9Cve=
ndor lock=E2=80=9D and keep competitors out for decades. But the recent Lat=
tice Mesh announcements suggest the rise of a more open, flexible and adapt=
able approach=E2=80=A6

What=E2=80=99s in it for Anduril? While Keane didn=E2=80=99t say so outrigh=
t, the firm is clearly betting that an open door on Lattice Mesh is good fo=
r business, much as Apple benefits from letting third parties develop appli=
cations for their iPhones: More third-party options make the underlying pro=
duct more useful, so it sells better.

It goes both ways: yes, 3rd-party applications, sensors, and even weapons w=
ill make Lattice more valuable; what is critical, though, is that Lattice w=
ill make those applications, sensors, and weapons more viable, less expensi=
ve, and more effective. That is the power of platforms.

Anduril + Palantir
------------------

One of the questions that I had about Anduril previously was how they fit a=
longside Palantir, which has a similar operating system-type platform appro=
ach to data, but which operates more at the battlefield commander level. Th=
at Breaking Defense article actually gets at an important distinction:

This open-door, decentralized approach is not unique to Lattice Mesh. Indee=
d, Lattice is just one of several pieces of the military=E2=80=99s evolving=
 capability to share intelligence and transmit orders across US and allied =
forces on land, sea, air, space, and cyberspace =E2=80=94 known as Combined=
 Joint All-Domain Command & Control (CJADC2). Over time, the military has b=
acked off from one-size-fits-all approaches to CJADC2. Instead of imposing =
a single universal data standard and a single mega-network, it=E2=80=99s mo=
ving towards a =E2=80=9Cfederated=E2=80=9D approach that allows different s=
ystems for different niches but tries to make them all compatible.

That wasn=E2=80=99t obvious from the start, Palmieri emphasized. =E2=80=9CW=
hen we started off in January of 2023, we thought =E2=80=A6 we could find o=
ne capability that would do all those things,=E2=80=9D she told Breaking De=
fense. But through a series of quarterly Global Information Dominance Exper=
iments, =E2=80=9Cwhat we realized was that there wasn=E2=80=99t a single da=
ta integration layer that you could select as best of breed across all thos=
e organizations and missions =E2=80=A6 What you needed at the strategic and=
 operational level for data integration was different than what we needed a=
t a tactical level.=E2=80=9D

When CDAO released the initial operational toolkit for CJADC2 =E2=80=94 off=
icially called the =E2=80=9CMinimum Viable Capability=E2=80=9D and publicly=
 announced in February =E2=80=94 it focused on strategic coordination at th=
e four-star Combatant Commands. But data-sharing tools for headquarters sta=
ff aren=E2=80=99t suitable for combat units, Palmieri said. Headquarters ne=
ed huge amounts of information to produce detailed plans in hours or days; =
frontline commanders need much smaller volumes of data, but they need it ri=
ght now. That second niche is where Lattice Mesh came in. =E2=80=9CThe data=
 mesh capability is not the answer for everything,=E2=80=9D Palmieri said. =
=E2=80=9CWhat we found with the data mesh that Anduril provided was it was =
really good at that low-latency data exchange.=E2=80=9D

It=E2=80=99s the first niche that Palantir is aiming to fill, and as furthe=
r evidence that these two approaches are compatible is this news from Bloom=
berg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-12-06/defense-startups-=
palantir-anduril-to-save-battlefield-data-to-train-ai-models ) :

Software company Palantir Technologies Inc. and weapons maker Anduril Indus=
tries Inc. plan to accelerate the use of artificial intelligence in the US =
military and are inviting other companies to join the effort. Under an agre=
ement announced Friday, battlefield information created by sensors, vehicle=
s, robots and weapons will be collected by Anduril=E2=80=99s Lattice softwa=
re and then pulled into a secure Palantir platform that will prepare the da=
ta for use in AI training and development. The data gathered would includin=
g information classified at the highest levels of secrecy.

This is the exact structure laid out above: Lattice is the operating system=
 for the battlefield, meant for in-the-moment decision-making, while Palant=
ir is the ultimate source of truth, meant for analysis and battle-planning.=
 The needs and corresponding priorities are completely different, so it mak=
es sense that different companies are doing the respective work; what is cr=
itical, however, is that they work together, and this agreement is very goo=
d news in that regard.

Stepping back, there are three broader points to make.

First, I expect the =E2=80=9Coperating system of the U.S. military=E2=80=9D=
 category to be exceptionally lucrative, and frankly, it=E2=80=99s hard to =
think of two companies and founding teams that deserve it more than Anduril=
 and Palantir. Both companies were founded at the height of tech anti-Ameri=
can and anti-military sentiment, and both sets of founders were derided in =
many quarters for their choices; they=E2=80=99ve earned this opportunity.

Second, it=E2=80=99s not a surprise that this advancement is coming from te=
ch. One, there is the platform concept I wrote about above. Two, the idea o=
f co-opetition =E2=80=94 because all of tech needs to work together at some=
 level =E2=80=94 lends itself well to building out appropriate systems at d=
ifferent levels of the stack that work together. Three, the venture capital=
 funding model is the only way these companies could fund the R&D to even g=
et in the Pentagon=E2=80=99s door in the first place.

Third, Palantir is in particularly good shape, because it=E2=80=99s approac=
h is aligned with Enterprise Philosophy and the First Wave of AI ( https://=
stratechery.com/2024/enterprise-philosophy-and-the-first-wave-of-ai/?access=
_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS=
IsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAi=
OiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWN=
oZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L2VudGVycHJpc2UtcGhpbG9zb3BoeS1hbmQtdGhlLWZpcnN0LXdhdmUtb2=
YtYWkvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MzY5NDcyOTEsImlhdCI6MTczNDM1NTI5MSwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6L=
y9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpy=
ZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU=
4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.OTbm4AfDzN8bZY433JazMsq1NEyqGB=
vXtcSlUseUr7PMYEzW98ePA0pSu5RVvOg6hzncGdc91WCUqkgHt-Aomzsc5YQndhCdo-JaD9Gqq=
spwJpdpX9PeNqHAjaQj9eJ3W-cnT8WVI55DC5-61JHGQXJg_f64xkj8EEibfBOj-d_dG3L_aiCc=
axE9becVMzn95EMH2gXk3qNi2ReLO8d6HB835zcUdTVAnPyzolfFEhxK10r1rlGNRgHckEogEhj=
6ju_rY-JoYEs91m_F5IM76bBk37OJ1OT5Au7kzzLadu2iBI8i_r8OI6Tq0P8VNjtXEbW3uOfa0p=
0vW18LymYLyw ) ; Anduril is much more of a pure play military operation. At=
 the same time, the platform aspects of Lattice have the potential to have =
a broader impact in terms of startup opportunities, particularly when it co=
mes to manufacturing. I=E2=80=99m happy to help Luckey get the word out in =
that regard.

